defaultWritten evidence from CTC (SRN 026)default&#xa0;
defaultCTC, the national cycling charity, was founded in 1878. CTC has 70,000 members and supporters, provides a range of information and legal services to cyclists,
default organises cycling events, and represents the interests of cyclists and cycling on issues of public policy.
default&#xa0;
defaultSummarydefault&#xa0;
defaultThe strategic road network can, in the words of the Government’s 
default‘Action for Roads’ policy
default, be “a barrier for walkers and cyclists.” Large
default junctions are dangerous locations for cyclists and the very high perceived risk of
default cycling 
defaultmeans cycle trips are suppressed. In some cases 
defaultmajor roads are the only practical route available to cyclists, but conditions are unacceptably dangerous on the car
defaultriageway, or where off-carriageway facilities cross junctions
default, such as slip roads or large roundabouts
default.
default&#xa0;
defaultCTC welcomes the statements 
defaulton pages 44 and 45 of the 
default‘
defaultAction for Roads
default’
default paper 
defaultto
default provid
defaulte
default better provision for cyclists on the strategic road network. 
defaultThis followed an announcement by the Prime Minister in August 2012 to ‘cycle proof’ major road schemes
default, while the Shadow Transport Secretary has promised an obligation on authorities “to ‘cycle proof’ new policies and projects.”
default&#xa0;
defaultWhile 
defaultthis announcement 
defaultand commitment is welcome
default,
default CTC remains 
defaultconcerned
default that
default the means by which the Government will ensure that provision for cyclists improves on – and around – the strategic road network is 
defaultcurrently 
defaultineffective, and needs to be radically improved.
default 
default&#xa0;
defaultCTC recomm
defaultends that the Highways Age
defaultncy 
defaultmust be tasked not just to 
defaultassess conditions for cyclists and not make conditions worse, but to ensure that conditions substantially improve for cyclists. 
defaultDesign guidance on cycle provision produced by the Agency must be stren
defaultgthened and brought into line with better 
defaultquality standards produced by the Department for Transport
default.
default&#xa0;
defaultCTC believes that the National Transport Model has key flaws – particularly in the assumptions it uses of the growth of cycle use in future years – and s
defaultuggests that providing infrastructure to satisfy the outcomes of an inaccurate model risks wasting resources and locking future generations into unsustainable levels of motor traffic use.
default&#xa0;
defaultHow will the policies set out in the Government’s “Action for Roadsdefault” command paper improve the strategic road network for all road users, whilst also improving the environment?default&#xa0;
defaultHow does the Government’s policy for roads link with planning for other transport modes?default&#xa0;
defaultIn August the Prime Minister 
defaultacknowledged in a 
defaultstatement
default the need to tackle problems on the strategic road network and to ‘cycle proof’ major roads schemes.
default 
default In a welcome act of cross-party consensus, the then Shadow Secretary of State for Transport, Maria Eagle MP also promised “
defaultan obligation to ‘cyc
defaultle-proof’ new policies and projects
default.”
default&#xa0;
defaultThe ‘Action for Roads’ paper gives a little more detail on the intention behind the ‘cycle proofing’ statement. CTC believes this is a worthy and important principle, but past experience leads us to fear that the qua
defaultlity of implementation will not live up to the promise.
default&#xa0;
defaultIn the early 2000s CTC, along with other groups representing walkers and horse riders, 
defaultworked with the Highways Agency to draw up lists of
default schemes where crossings needed to be improved.
default This was desi
defaultgnated as the Non-Motorised User Crossings 
defaultImprovement 
defaultProgramme, but funding pledged to support the programme was redirected to other projects.
default 
default&#xa0;
defaultWhen the Programme was evaluated in 2008 (the last date for which 
defaultinformation is
default available), only 259 (22%) o
defaultut of 1,159 schemes had been completed. A further 46% had been deleted
default from the Programme;
default the outcome
default of 32%
default 
defaultis 
defaultunknown.
default  Not only have relatively few of these schemes been progressed, CTC still hears of newly built schemes where conditions for cyclists 
defaultare likely to be made worse, rather than improved. 
default&#xa0;
defaultCTC’s concerns about the way the strategic road network affects cycling include:
