default&#xa0;
defaultThe strategic road network is, in general, made up of two types of road: purpose built dual carriageway/motorway 
defaultand historically strategic road alignments which have been gradually upgraded. 
default&#xa0;
defaultOf these two types of road, the 
defaultupgraded old road
default represents the biggest problem, partly because they are in close proxi
defaultmity to heavily populated areas, often passing through 
defaulturban areas or rural areas with multiple minor road junctions. Purpose built
default motorways
default or new dual carriageways
default use 
defaultgrade
default-
defaultseparated crossings
default for most minor roads and rights of way
default, whereas the process of gradual upgrading has meant that older roads sever
default 
defaultlocal road 
defaultand rights of way 
defaultnetwork. 
defaultThe ‘Action for Roads’ document acknowledges that “some major roads, particularly those built in the early days of mass-motoring, can create a barrier between two sides” (p. 45).
default&#xa0;
defaultAlthough thousands of examples exist, 
defaultone can be found on
default the A27 in West Sussex
default, a road that forms
default part of the strategic road network serving the South Coast. In many places it bypasses towns and villages, however, in other places it remains in the same location as the road had been at the st
defaultart of the motoring age
default (see Figures 1 and 2 below). Whereas then traffic would have been light and crossing would have been 
defaultsimple
default, it is now a fast, very heavi
defaultly used dual carriageway, with over 27 thousands vehicles per day.
default&#xa0;
defaultMinor roads which used to 
defaultcross the road are now closed to motor traffic
default, or accessible only as single-facing junctions
default, while pedestrians and cyclists are supposed to wait for gaps in two streams of 70 mph traffic to cross
default.
default There are three potential routes between
default the villages of 
defaultSlindon and Walberton, including minor roads, a bridleway and a busier B-road.
default All of these routes 
defaulthave
default level c
defaultrossings with the A27.
default&#xa0;
defaultThe A27 in the 1920s (left) and today (right)
default 
defaultsevering local trips between villages.
default 
default&#xa0;
defaultHundreds of these minor roads hav
defaulte been cut in road upgrades over the years, with similar impact
defaults on the rights of way network. These problems abound across the network.
default&#xa0;
defaultIn other places, where the major road served 
defaultas crucial link joining minor roads, or the sole link between communities
default, the lack of proper adjacent facilities for cyclists, or inadequate quality of treatment of crossings of major junctions, means that the link has become unusable for all but the least risk averse cyclists. 
