defaultowever, the commitment to mitigate the problem is contingent on 
defaultkey 
defaultindividuals
default within the Agency
default, and the mechanism
defaults to embed this in Highways Ag
defaultency (and local authority) practice are presently vague and undeveloped. 
defaultAlthough each scheme must go through a No
defaultn-Motorised User Audit process, in CTC’s experience, 
defaultthis often appears to have failed to deal with the problems, or has 
defaultnot generated 
defaultadequat
defaulte
default solutions.
default&#xa0;
defaultLack of evidence of cycle use should not be used as a reason not to provide routesdefault&#xa0;
defaultPart of the problem remains that in many places where roads are being upgraded or junction capacity increased, conditions for cycling are already very hazardo
defaultus and 
defaultconsequently cycling levels are minimal. However, just because conditions are poor, does not mean that no one wants to use the route – on the example given above, there may have bee
defaultn many people who in the distant
default past travelled between Slindon and 
defaultWalberton by foot, cycle and even horse
default. 
defaultToday, though 
defaultonly a
default flat
default 
defaultmile divides these villages
default, such trips 
defaultare greatly
default deterred
default the need to cross the 
defaultriver of traffic that is the 
defaultA27. 
default&#xa0;
defaultFurthermore CTC campaigners have regularly faced problems with the way
default the HA treats cyclists when upgrading routes or junctions. 
default&#xa0;
defaultCase study: Jundefaultcdefaulttion 9 M3default&#xa0;
defaultSince dangerous crossings or narrow, low quality routes are
default often
default little used, making the case for their improvement is hard. 
defaultThe lack of evidence of use of routes 
defaultthat are already severed means that attempts by local campaigners to argue for improvements, new – grade separated crossings – or parallel facilities, are often ignored or
default underplayed by HA contractors.
default 
default&#xa0;
defaultProposals to 
defaultupgrade junction 
default9 
defaultof the 
defaultM3 involved 
defaultnarrowing the available space for footway users alongside an overbridge to provide a third carriageway lane. The Highways Agency ignored the fact that the 
defaultfootpath provided at the time of the original construction of the junction
default was part of the National C
defaultycle Network and failed to engage with either cyclists or pedestrians with regard to the status and use of the route.
default 
default&#xa0;
defaultCase study: Junction 13 M1default&#xa0;
defaultWhen redesigning junction 13 of the M1 (junction with the A421), the HA initially omitted any cycle provision. After the public inquiry inspector upheld objections to this from CTC’s local campaigner, a revised (but still inadequate) scheme was agreed. How
defaultever it was incompletely implemented when the junction was opened, leaving cyclists to negotiate an unsurfaced mud-bath or a major roundabout.  
default&#xa0;
defaultAfter protests led to this being remedied, the HA introduced signing which led cyclists straight to a dangerou
defaults roundabout, instead of connecting with a bridge built by the local authority to avoid this. It took months of campaigning before correct signing was installed – almost 3 years after the new junction had been opened.  Meanwhile, the scheme’s inadequacies 
defaultmean that a huge opportunity has been missed to encourage people to cycle to 
defaultwork at the nearby Amazon depot, or to Cranfield University.
default&#xa0;
defaultCTC recommends that the Highways Agency provide better training for staff
default and contractors
default in how to design for cyclis
defaultts, and develops more robust procedures to 
defaultensure that schemes actually develop 
defaultimproved 
defaultnetworks for walking and cycling, not just mitigating the damage caused by existing or new roads.
default 
defaultThe programme of works to retrofit improvements must continue in future years, with more of the Non-Motorised User Crossings schemes progressed.
default&#xa0;
defaultCTC also recommends that the 
defaultsections of the 
defaultstandards document used by the Highways Agency, the ‘Design Manua
defaultl for Roads and Bridges’
default, 
defaultbe 
defaultoverhaul
defaulted
default to bring it in line with other cycling design guidance. Dimensions and designs in this document fall well below the standard of 
defaultother international and national best practice
default, presenting local authority engineers wit
defaulth confusing and conflicting double standards, and permitting designers to opt for the minimal standard design
default, rather than a high quality solution.
default&#xa0;
defaultc) defaultUse of the strategic road network by local motorised traffic, which could be shifted to sustainable modedefaults.default defaultPrevious research has suggested that congestion on the strategic road network is often due to short trips that use parts of the strategic network.
default 
defaultIf conditions for local trips on and across the strategic road network could be improved
default for cyclists
default, th
defaulte benefits may be conferred on the network itself, by reducing 
defaultthe level of traffic using the strategic road network to m
defaultake short intra-urban journeys. This could alleviate congested locations though demand-side, rather than supply-side, measures.
default&#xa0;
defaultCreati
defaultng access to the strategic road network for local motor traffic in some cases also induces more traffic onto local roads through attracting longer trip distances and enhancing the perceived ease of access by car. In this respect, reduction in the permeabil
defaultity of the strategic road network for motor traffic is 
defaultbeneficial, but access across the network for cyclists and
default pedestrians must be maintained. 
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
defaultTable 1.2 of the report (p 18) shows that although traffic on the strategic road network grew up until 2006, since then it has been static. While some of that period included a substantial recession, 
defaultthe lack of growth in 2006 (before the recession) and subsequently, together with the gradual decline in traffic on the rest of the road network, suggests that the outputs of the National Transport Model
default, which have persistently predicted sustained motor t
defaultraffic growth,
default are flawed.
default&#xa0;
defaultOne small example of the out of date baseline data that the NTM uses can be found in its figures on cycling. The NTM assumes that 
defaultaverage cycle trip length (originally a little over 2 miles in 2010) will rise very slightly, befo
defaultre falling back to a figure b
defaultelow the 2010 figure by 2035, whereas car trips will continue to increase in length.
default 
defaultHowever, in reality, cycle trip lengths are 48% longer in 2012 than 
defaultthey were 10 years earlier, far higher than the inpu
defaultt level used in the m
defaultodel, while car trips have not increased in length (
defaultsee 
defaultfigure 3).
default&#xa0;
defaultThis extension in the average trip length is likely due to the growth of cycling amongst long-distance sport cycling and 
defaultcycle commuting amongst older adults. 
defaultCTC suspects that this is supported by the rise in value and quality of cycles, which is likely to make 
defaultlonger distance trips more practical. 
default&#xa0;
defaultIn addition, CTC believes that the Transport Model is underplaying the
default long-term
default impact of electric bikes, which make up 
defaultjust 1% of the market at present, but in mature markets, such as the Netherlands, amount to 15% of total
default bike sales
default.
default Bikes with electrical assistance will lead to further increases in trip length, increasing the li
defaultkelihood that cycle trips will a) displace more car trips and b) intersect with, or require the use of, the strategic road network.
default 
default&#xa0;
defaultThis is but one – 
defaultalbeit minor - example of how CTC
default feel
defaults
default that the 
defaultparameters used within
default the National Transport Model are
default inaccurate. 
defaultTransport academics have pointed out that
default other aspects of the models calculations are flawed
default and biased 
defaulttowards inflated traffic growth.
default 
defaultCTC
default suggest
defaults
default that the model needs to be substantially overhauled and improved before its forecasts are u
defaultsed to determine policy.
default&#xa0;
defaultIf
default 
defaultthe Model’s output is accepted as inevitable and the network is planned to meet the growth in motor traffic, then that growth has a greater chance of materialising. On the other hand, a more radical suite of policy measures to 
defaultreduce motor traffic and shift to sustainable modes could produce a very different result, and one that would 
defaultbe substantially 
defaultless costly, result in far fewer emissions and be more appealing to 
defaultthose communities potentially blighted by the projected huge 
defaultincreases in traffic.
default&#xa0;
default&#xa0;
defaultThe greatest impact on reliability 
defaultcomes from road crashes, not necessarily congestion, which is 
defaultusually predictable and can be accommodated for
default in trip timing and route choice
default. Reducing the risk of crashes for all road users should, we feel, be the focus of efforts to improve reliability. The use of lower speed limits, enforced by average speed camer
defaultas, has shown to be effective in this regard.
default One area of technological improvement that should be investigated further is that of intelligent speed adaptation, by which maximum vehicle speeds could be determined independently and 
defaultvaried
default to 
defaultaccommodate 
defaultthe
default 
defaultweather 
defaultconditions or density of traffic
default. 
default 
